<b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Greece" title="Portal:Greece">Greece Portal</a></b><br />
&#160;<span class="noprint plainlinksneverexpand" style="white-space: nowrap; font-size:xx-small;"><a href="/wiki/Template:History_of_Greece" title="Template:History of Greece">v</a>&#160;•&#160;<a href="/wiki/Template_talk:History_of_Greece" title="Template talk:History of Greece"><span title="Discussion about this template.">d</span></a>&#160;•&#160;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:History_of_Greece&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:History_of_Greece&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow"><span style="color:#002bb8;" title="You can edit this template. Please use the preview button before saving.">e</span></a></span>&#160;</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The <b>Minoan civilization</b> was a <a href="/wiki/Bronze_Age" title="Bronze Age">Bronze Age</a> civilization which arose on the island of <a href="/wiki/Crete" title="Crete">Crete</a>. The Minoan culture flourished from approximately <a href="/wiki/27th_century_BC" title="27th century BC">2700</a> to <a href="/wiki/15th_century_BC" title="15th century BC">1450</a> BC; afterwards, <a href="/wiki/Mycenaean_Greece" title="Mycenaean Greece">Mycenaean Greek</a> culture became dominant at Minoan sites in Crete. Rediscovered at the beginning of the 20th century, at first through the work of the British archaeologist <a href="/wiki/Sir_Arthur_Evans" title="Sir Arthur Evans" class="mw-redirect">Sir Arthur Evans</a>, Minoan Crete took its historic place, as Will Durant said in 1939, as "the first link in the European chain."<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
